{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f54427e5-592f-4da8-b2dc-991e87e912f7","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a trace (e.g., 30 seconds)\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n### 5. Copy the trace file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 6. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n---\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't in the container, use `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar instead — it exposes a REST API for on-demand trace collection without modifying the app container.\n- For a **lower-level** trace, use `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first to confirm CPU is spent in managed code before collecting a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"729e6228-be0a-4212-9b09-bd641f0846d0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU usage. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":412,"requestId":"9816:11A36E:C969DE:E9EF0C:69F400E4"},"id":"0de40bb4-d01a-4f03-a8bc-ca334a1aa200","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:25:01.419Z","parentId":"5d840a0a-9937-432f-8952-53240dc1f105"}
